column13: 4452. Clarke, H. Feb. 18. Locks, permutation.-The lock is described with reference to a padlock form, but may be applied to safes &c. It consists of two locking-discs B, B' with divided pins C, C', the discs being capable of rotation on the hub k of a setting-plate or casing K. The upper disc carries a dial plate G with push-buttons g<1> corresponding to the number of pins, and resting on radial springs h, shown in Fig. 2, with the dial plate removed. The arm A' of the bow is connected to the disc B<1> and the arm A to the disc B. A coiled spring M connects the disc B' and the setting-plate K, and tends to separate the arms when the pins are disengaged, the necessary relative motion of the discs being allowed by a pin and slot connection. By depressing only the pins C<1> which form the combination, the divisions of all the pins are brought opposite the meeting surfaces of the discs, allowing the arms to be opened. When closing the lock, the arms are brought together and the two discs then move together relatively to the setting-plate, causing cam cavities k<2> in the latter to restore the combination pins to their locked position. Springs F, F<1>, or their equivalents, act frictionally on the pins to maintain them in any position into which they may be pushed. On releasing the arms, the spring M causes them to slightly separate, causing a tension between the discs. To prevent picking by feeling, a plate N, with projections n, is attached to the setting-plate, so that in the normal locked position, when there is a tension between the discs, the projections n register with the radial springs h and prevent any of the pins being operated. On slightly closing the arms, thus removing the tension, the projections are brought into register with spaces h<1> between the springs, and any pin can be depressed without disclosing the combination. The depression of an idle pin locks the discs and necessitates a re-setting before the lock can be opened. The ends of the arms interlock to prevent separation of the parts.

column12: Improvements in and applicable to Circular Knitting Machines.
column13: 16. Clarke, H. Jan. 2. Circular knitting-machines.-Relates to machines with latch needles and oscillating needle cams and thread-carriers and fixed needle cylinders, and the object of the invention is to fashion pant. legs, shirt sleeves, &c. by throwing the thread-carrier out of or into action, and so to vary the number of needles fed at either or both selvages and to splice the fabric at any part. Any number of articles can be made on one machine. The cam ring c, Fig. 10, has a fixed uptbrow c', a sliding down-throw c<3> operated by the needles themselves, and two vertically-sliding switch cams c<4>; its outer rim is toothed, and it is oscillated by being geared up to a slide which is operated by a rocking lever d<2>, link d<1>, and crank-wheel d geared to the main shaft. A bracket on the ring works between a pair of projections on, and so operates, the sinker cam. The sinkers slide horizontally in tricks in a ring e<1>. The splicing-thread carrier f <3> and the main carrier f<1>are pivoted to a bracket f carried by the cam ring. A spring tends to draw the splicing- carrier into the operative position ; a friction washer causes the main carrier to stay in any position in which it is put. The latch guard f <8> is slotted to allow the carriers to move to the inoperative position. A fixed cam f<9> acts on a truck f<5> on the heel of the splicing-carrier, and, according as it is shaped, causes the carrier to splice at any part. A similar truck on the heel of the main thread-carrier f<1> is acted on by two cams g<1>, one at each end of the stroke ; these cams are carried by rings working in a groove in the bed. These rings are moved in opposite directions by pinions g<4>, g<5> and ratchet-wheels g<7>, each of which is acted on by a pair of pawls carried by a slide operated by a rocking lever g<14> and cam g<13> ; the pawls are put in or out of action by bluffs operated through a link g<11> from the pattern chain o. The threads h, k pass from spools h<1>, k<1> through eyes k<2> and feeding-tubes, under pivoted shoes k<4>, over the spring take-up k<5> or h<5>, and down through eyes k<6> to the carriers. When a catch i<6> is released, by means of the link i<7>, lever i<8>, i<9>, and a pattern lug, the spring-actuated slide i<3> is set free, and the splicing-thread is cut between the fixed blade i<1> and the movable blade i<2>. The pattern chain o has lugs of two different heights, and passes round adjustable pulleys o' and fixed pulleys o‹ and round a pulley actuated by a ratchet-wheel and pawl operated by a cam and lever. The bits act on levers, pivoted at o<8>, which control the fashioning and yarn delivering. One lever o<9> acts through a link l<4>, and disengages a lever l<1> from a notch in a bar l; the bar l, when released, is pulled by a spring, and shifts the belt on to the loose pulley. The stop-motion may be operated by hand. When a pattern lever is operated, a pivoted lever o<13> will hold it in place until a further lug operates another lever o<10>, and so puts the hold-out lever o<13> out of gear. This lever o<10> may be operated by hand, and may put the pawl of the pattern-driving ratchet-wheel out of gear, so that the chain can be moved by hand.

column12: Improved Construction of Coupling for Railway Vehicles.
column13: 24,435. Clarke, H. Nov. 7. Couplings, automatic.-At each end of the vehicle, a trumpet-shaped tube C and a bar D, having a slot E, are connected to a cross-bar A of the usual spring-controlled draw-bar B, a crossrod L ensuring strength and rigidity. A bent lever F, pivoted to the tube C, carries at one end a short rod G hanging through, and capable of a rocking motion in, slots H in the tube C. When two vehicles come together, the bar D of one vehicle enters the tube C of the other, the rods G ride on the top of the bars D, fall into the slots E, and, on the rebound of the vehicle, assume a vertical position and engage with the lower slots H. Uncoupling is effected by lifting the short rods G, preferably by means of a bar I having handles J and a crank K engaging the other end of the lever F. The bars D have a free side movement to facilitate coupling and uncoupling on curved portions of the railway. The usual draw-bar hook is preferably situated between the tube C and the rod D, for use with wagons not fitted with this device.

column12: Improvements in and applicable to Circular Knitting Machines.
column13: 13. Clarke, H. Jan. 1. Circular knitting - m a - chines. -Relates to improvements on the invention described in Specifications No. 18,644, A.D. 1892, and No. 8559, A.D. 1895. The c a m ring and thread-guides are rotated or reciprocated by means of a clutch which connects a shaft either with a bevel - wheel or with a spur-wheel. The bevel-wheel is geared to the driving-shaft direct, but the spur-wheel is in gear with a rack constantly reciprocated by a. crank and wheel. The clutch, is moved by an arm on a shaft 50 having a frame 51 in which works a cam 52 on a shaft 53 rotated by a ratchetwheel 63 and pawl 56 on a constantly-reciprocated arm 55. During rotary knitting the pawl 56 strikes a projection 58 and is lifted out of gear with its wheel 63, and the shaft 53 is at rest. When reciprocating knitting is required, a lug on the pattern chain acts through levers and moves the projection 58, and allows the shaft 53 to be rotated and the shaft 50 and consequently the clutch to be moved. The wheel 63 moves three teeth, after which the fashioning-mechanism acts through a lever 64 to raise a bluff 65 which stops any further motion ; at the same time a lever raises a pawl and stops the pattern chain. When the fashioning is completed, the fashioning-mechanism returns the bluff to its normal position, and the shaft 53 is again rotated and the clutch moved. A falling lever then racks the pattern chain one link, and the parts come to their normal position. The needle cylinder is raised during the knitting of heel, toe, and calf by the usual incline and lever arrangement operated from a subsidiary pattern chain, the actuating ratchet-wheel having a long tooth making the pawl inactive till the pattern chain is racked one tooth by means of a lever and lug on the main pattern chain. The main thread-carrier 1 is pivoted at 1<a>, and the striping-carriers 2, 3, 4 at 2<a>, to a bracket 5 hinged to a bracket 5" on the wheel 6. which also carries the usual cam ring 8.. The tails of the carriers are acted on by cams 1<c> on shafts 1<d> having notched wheels 1<e> and springs 1<f> to ensure the proper amount of rotation and starwheels 1<g>. Inclines raised and lowered by levers acted on by lugs on the pattern chain act on the star-wheels, and throw one carrier into action and another out of action at the same time. The yarn is thrown in at the left-hand side of a particular needle, while the last yarn is thrown out at the right-hand side of the same needle. The inactive yarns wrap around guides 95, 94 carried by arms on the brackets 5 ; the guide 94 prevents twisting of the yarns between the carrier eyes and itself, and so allows each thread to be fed without dragging another with it.

column12: Secure access system for goods delivery
column13: An access system has a central server which generates an access code for a lock restricting access to a target site, and communicates the access code to a recipient to enable remote access to the site, e.g. for the purpose of goods delivery and collection. In response to a request for an access code, the request including a lock identifier, the server validates the request based on authentication information provided in the request (which can be a requester identifier, or a postal address of the lock), and, if the request is valid, generates an access code based on seed information for the identified lock. The lock validates the entered access code based on a defined algorithm in dependence on stored seed information in the lock, and unlocks in response to successful validation. Single use codes, multiple use codes, or codes that are valid for a limited period, can be used. The systems allows a flexible goods distribution system to be provided.
column15: CLARKE HENRY

column12: Improvements in and relating to Automatic Fluid Pressure Train Brakes.
column13: 21,743. Clarke, W. H. Oct. 31. Brakes.-Relates to automatic air brakes, and consists in providing a special valve which, by reducing the pressure in the brake cylinder to a predetermined limit, presents the skidding of the wheels as the train slows down, no matter how hard the brakes have been applied originally. The Figure shows the valve as placed between the auxiliary cylinder C and a standard Westing- house triple valve. When the brakes are applied, air passes through the passage c and past the valve d<2> to the triple valve, and thence by the passage B to a pipe b leading to the brake cylinder. Air flows from the passage B by the duct a to the interior of the valve d<3>, and thence through openings in the parts d<4> and d<9> to the diaphragm d<1>. This diaphragm is about one-third larger than the other d, so that both are moved to the right to close the valve d<2> and open the valve d'. Air can then escape slower from the brake cylinder to the atmosphere through the port a<1>, until the pressure is about 40 lbs. to the square inch, the leverage of the rigging being altered to suit. When the pressure in the brake cylinder is sufficiently reduced, the pressure on the diaphragm d moves both diaphragms to the left, and closes the valve d<3>. The valve d<2>, however, owing to its connection with the diaphragm, remains closed.
column15: CLARKE WILLIAM HENRY

column13: The present disclosure generally relates to wireless devices, and more particularly, to battery powered wireless devices and methods of operating said devices using a scheduled communication time. A first device and a second device of a building control system may communicate wirelessly during scheduled communication times. The second device may enter a listening state during the scheduled communication times, and may enter a non-listening state between at least some of the scheduled communication times. A plurality of user inputs may cause a corresponding communication between the first device and the second device. The user inputs may identify active periods of a day that user input is more likely to occur, and inactive periods of the day that user input is less likely to occur. The second device may be maintained in the listening state more during active periods than during inactive periods.

column12: Surgical Apparatus for use in Performing Operations within the Cranium.
column13: 22,455. Clarke, R. H. Oct. 2. Brain centres, localizing and treating.-Relates to apparatus for performing operations within the cranium and constitutes a surgical form of the instrument described in Specification 18,297/12 for gauging the position of and reaching any desired point within a closed surface. The apparatus comprises essentially (a) an indicator serving to give a mechanical representation of the position of the required point within the cranium with reference to three planes at rightangles, and provided with a finder, the adjustments of which to reach the desired point may be indicated on fixed scales ; and (b) an operative instrument, to be applied to the cranium under treatment, which is substantially similar to the indicator, but is provided with an actual surgical probe or like instrument having adjustments similar to those of the finder, whereby it can be set so that it may be projected longitudinally directly to the point within the cranium corresponding to the representation of the point for which the finder on the indicator is set. The operative instrument comprises (1) a cubical frame 32, 33, 34, Fig. 17, the lower part of which serves as a head vice to position the frame correctly on the skull, (2) a stage 82, 83 which may be attached to any one of the sides or to the top of, the cubical frame, and is fitted with rackbars 85, 86, (3) a compound slide rest comprising bars sliding on the rack-bars 85, 86 of the stage and connected by two rack-bars 94, 95 which form guides for the upper member of the slide rest, (4) a so-called pillar 103 carried by the slide rest, (5) a finder socket 104 mounted with radial adjustment on the pillar 103, and (6) an operative instrument, shown as a ' needle ' formed of two conductors for producing electrolytic lesions within the brain, mounted on compound graduated slides on the socket 104 so that it may be projected directly to a given brain centre when the various adjustments have been correctly set in accordance with the readings obtained from the indicator. The lower part of the cubical frame is positioned on the cranium in relation to the assumed zero planes by means of ear cones 39, head-cramps 67, 77, an occipital bar 25, and a mask or bridle comprising hooks 45 for the orbits, cheek pieces 47, 48, and a mouth bit. Preliminary gauging of the skull under treatment is effected by means of the apparatus shown in Fig. 15, which is clamped on to the vertical members 34 of the cubical frame and which consists of a needle 160 carried by a graduated stem 161 adjustable lengthways in a slide block 162, which is itself adjustable along a graduated horizontal bar 163. The slide block carries a removable cover 169 held in place by a screw 170 and serving to clamp the stem 161 to the block after adjustment. An adjustable index or zero pointer 172 is carried by a rod 173 slidable in the block 162 and clamped in position by a screw 174.

column13: 6199. Pruce, H. C. March 16. Fastenings for doors; registering.-In the type of lock described in Specification 20,735/05, means are provided for preventing the re-operation of the inside auxiliary bolt after it has been withdrawn to enable the door to be opened, and a register is provided actuated by the indicator plate. The inside bolt is connected by bell-crank mechanism to a spindle 14 passing through the door and carrying within the back casing a follower 11 which is thus rotated as the bolt is shot. The follower has an arm 19 which engages, when the indicator-plate 1 is in its ' vacant ' position, with a projection 20 thereon, and prevents the operation of the bolt until the indicator is raised. When therefore the door has been opened from the inside, it is impossible for the occupant to re-shoot the inside bolt to prevent the door from properly closing after his exit. The register is actuated by a bell-crank 21 or other lever one arm of which bears on the top of the indicator plate.

column13: 11,188. Pruce, H. C. May 23. Indicators, " engaged " and like.-Relates to coinfreed locks in which the indicator is moved when the bolt is withdrawn from outside. The coin 7, which couples the slide 1 and the bolt 2 in the known manner, turns the pivoted lever 5 which lifts the indicating-plate 11. This is held by a gravity or spring catch 12 in its raised position, the lower portion of the catch resting against the two-armed follower 17, 18 of the inside handle. When the handle is turned in either direction, one arm withdraws the bolt by bearing on a shoulder 20, and the other raises the catch 12, allowing the indicator to drop to the "vacant" position. In locks where a key may be used to withdraw the main bolt and a snib bolt simultaneously, as described in Specification No. 19,439, A.D. 1907, the catch 12 is provided with a lower extension 27, so that, when the key is used, the catch is moved by it, and the indicating-plate falls.

column13: 3161. Pruce, H. C. Feb. 8. Fastenings for doors.-Relates to locks for lavatories, of the type in which the door is opened by being pushed inwards or pulled outwards after the insertion of a coin. A counterweighted detent 9, Fig. 7, having been removed from engagement with a shoulder 10 on the bolt 1 by prepayment, the operator presses in or pulls open the door, the striking- plate 18 forcing back the bolt, the end of which is shaped as shown in Fig. 8. The detent 9 is prevented from re-engaging the bolt before the door is closed from within by means of a slide 20, which, when the door is opened, is moved in the direction of the arrow, Fig. 8, so as to remove the cut-away portion 27 from the path of the arm 25 of the detent. The slide 20 is operated against the action of a spring 24 by a lever 19, which is rocked by a second spring-controlled slide 14 having a bevelled nose 17 co-operating with the striking-plate 18. To open the door from within, the occupant turns a spindle 31 by means of an internal handle, whereupon followers 32 withdraw the slide -o, thereby freeing the detent 9 from the bolt owing to the engagement of the bevelled shoulders 28 with the arm 25; and, during the continued rotation of the spindle, followers 33 withdraw the bolt. The door may be opened from without by an attendant by means of a key, which is inserted in a keyhole 37 and serves to withdraw the slide 20. An ' engaged ' indicator is operated by a lever 40,' which cooperates with a slide 38 operated by the internal bolt. The attendant can withdraw the internal bolt fiom without by the key that is used to withdraw the slide 20. Coin action, weight; coin-discharging mechanism.-The inserted coin C falls on to the tail 11 of the detent 9 and tilts it so as to remove the arm 25 from engagement with the shoulder 10 on the bolt, and, being supported between depending members on the casing and bolt, falls to the till as the bolt is forced back.

column12: Apparatus for Gauging the Position of and Directing Access to Points within Closed Surfaces.
column13: 18,297. Clarke, R. H. Aug. 8. Brain centres, localizing.-Relates to means for indicating or representing the position of a point inside a solid, and for replacing a part of the indicating-means by an operative instrument for the purpose of applying it to the point, in question. The apparatus is primarily intended for use in surgical operations on the brain, the instrument employed being described in Specification 22,455/12. The position of the point is defined by the usual x, y, z co-ordinates and three surfaces A, B, C are provided graduated by parallel lines to enable a pointer, preferably a star-shaped body 0 formed by the intersection of three wires parallel to the axes, to be set. The pointer is mounted on a graduated arm d carried by a graduated upright d' sliding in a block D<1>, which slides on a scale parallel to the remaining axes. Instead of three graduated planes, two may be employed, one with two sets of graduations at right-angles. The planes are preferably grids of wire or thread, and may be made adjustable, as shown in Fig. 7, to facilitate exact settings of scale. A convenient arrangement of grids composed of rods with scale variable by parallelogrammatic displacement of the framework is shown in Fig. 12, the indicating star 0 being carried at a known distance above a block R sliding on a pair of rods attached to blocks sliding on arms P<1>, P<2>. The blocks have pins to enclose the graduating rods, and the arms P<1>, P<2> are secured to spring-controlled sleeves on a sleeve sliding on a pillar N supporting the system of planes. A methol of mounting the graduation bars of the planes so as to allow of scalar adjustment is shown in Fig. 11. A cubical frame E is adapted to be placel around the planes and to carry on any face a graduated slide F<1>, upon which slides the base F<2> of a pillar H rotatable around its axis and carying a pivoted frame G<1> in which slides a " finder " G. As is shown in Fig. 5, every adjustment can be given to the " finder," and a surgical instrument, such as a probe or that alluded to above, is intended to take the place of the " finder " when any position sought has been located.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Gauging the Position of and Directing Access to Points within Closed Surfaces, applicable for Surgical Operations within the Cranium.
column13: 17,711. Clarke, R. H. Aug. 1. Brain centres, localizing; brain centres, treating.- Relates to improvements in apparatus for operating at points within surfaces such as the crania of animals such as is described in Specification 22,455/12, comprising a mounting for a finder probe, or operating-instrument facilitating all adjustments, and a setting-means therefor. The mounting consists of a turntable 68, rotatable on a fixed platform 67 and having parallel sides on which slide the ends 79 of a circular bridge 81; sliding on this bridge is a block 87 having pivoted to it a block 95 undercut to take a sliding toolholder 103. All the angular and sliding movements are fitted with reading scales and clamps, the angular setting of the tool - holder supporting- block 95 being shown on a scale 90 which itself can be set at any angle to the radius of the bridge 81 as shown by a scale 92. The turntable and its platform have concentric apertures as large as possible and the platform has four feet to fit in sockets in a setting apparatus as shown in Fig. 2, or in a head vice as shown in Fig. 8, in which the head is exactly positioned between a nasal bar 85 and occipital bar 86 by means of cramps 83, 84 ; the central point of the interaural axis determined by the ear cones 82 corresponding to the point of intersection of the zero threads of the setting - instrument. This consists of a base-plate 11 supporting co-ordinate planes of the kind described in Specification 18,297/12, the longitudinal or X - planes being carried by parallel bars 14, 15 adjustable according to a scale 20 to vary the scale for setting and secured by a clamp 21 ; the Y-lines being in two parts to the front and rear of the inter-aural line, and separately variable as to scale, the anterior set being variable about centres 29, 30 according to a scale 39, the posterior set being carried by bars 23, 24 similarly variable according to a scale 35, clamps being fitted to both adjustments. The vertical plane is carried by parallel bars 41, 42, Fig. 3, adjustable about centres 43, 44 according to a scale 47. An X, Y indicating pointer is carried by a sliding arm 53 with angular adjustment according to a scale 65, and a vertical rod 60 similarly adjustable carries a similar pointer which can be set to any point. The pointers having been set to any co-ordinate position desired by means of the indicator planes, a probe can be set in a variety of ways on the holder on the bridge 81, and any suitable setting can be obtained for employing the probe or operating tool.

column12: Instruments and method for suturing and ligation
column13: A laparscopic method and instrument for suturing and ligation of tissue in a body cavity of a patient through trocar tubes inserted into the cavity. First forceps have a needle on the end of a movable jaw to pierce the tissue and pass a surgical thread through it. Second forceps have a movable jaw and a groove through the ends of both jaws and transverse to the pivotal axis of the movable jaw for advancing a loose tie in the surgical thread through a trocar tube and into engagement with the tissue and tensioning or drawing up the tie to close the tissue and produce a secure knot. Preferably, the jaws of both forceps each have therein a groove for guiding the thread to avoid tearing the tissue and blades for cutting the excess thread when the suture is completed.

column12: Manufacture of and Improved Alimentary Product.
column13: 26,794. Clarke, F. H. L. Dec. 22. Cocoa preparations.-A preparation adapted for use in cases of dyspepsia consists of triturated cocoa beans, banana flour, milk powder, and malt extract. The bananas are peeled and the pulp is cut into strips, which are dried by exposure first to the sun and then to a current of hot air, reduced to a granular form, further dried by hot air, and finally ground to flour and sifted. The aroma lost is restored by bringing into contact with the granular material during desiccation, or with the powdered material during sifting, the vapour of the essential oil preferably obtained by subjecting the peel, either fresh or preserved in alcohol, to a pressure of 3-4 atmospheres and a temperature of 30‹ C. When the pressure is reduced to half an atmosphere, the ethers distil off and the essential oil is left. For making tablets, the banana flour is mixed with milk powder and malt extract, ground cocoa containing all its fat is then incorporated, and sugar is added, but for making powder or compressed cakes the cocoa is mixed with liquid, condensed, or dry milk, dried, ground, and mixed with the banana flour. Violent action during grinding and incorporation is avoided, to preserve the nitrogenous products in their natural state.
column15: CLARKE FRANK HENRY LAVANCHY

column12: Laparoscopy instruments and method for suturing and ligation
column13: An improved combined laparoscopic needle and forceps comprising an elongated parallelogram type of linkage suitable for insertion through a trocar and having first and second ends, a needle, means for mounting said needle on said first end for movement from a position in substantial alignment with said linkage, which permits it to pass through a trocar, to a position transverse to said linkage, handle means on said second end of said linkage for actuating said linkage to effect movement of said needle, and a forceps construction including jaw means mounted proximate said first end of said needle linkage and being formed from a portion of said linkage and a portion of the holder of the needle. An improved combined laparoscopic forceps, suture guide and cutter comprising an elongated parallelogram type of linkage which is sufficiently slender for passage through a trocar and having first and second ends, jaw means on said first end, and handle means on said second end for actuating said linkage to move said jaws, groove means associated with said jaws for receiving a suture to thus act as a suture guide, and cutter means mounted on said jaws for cutting a suture. An improved laparoscopic ligator comprising an elongated stem having first and second ends, a handle at said first end and suture guiding means at said second end, said suture guiding means being of substantially the same cross sectional dimension as said elongated stem for guiding a suture through a trocar. An improved method of performing a surgical operation by laparoscopy comprising the steps of inserting at least first and second trocars through the body of a patient at spaced locations, inserting a first instrument comprising the above described combined laparoscopic needle and forceps through said first trocar, inserting a second instrument comprising the above described laparoscopic forceps, suture guide and cutter through said second trocar, manipulating said first and second instruments in cooperating relationship with each other in a predetermined area to the central portion of a suture in position, withdrawing one of said instruments to bring the end of the suture outside of the patient's body, tying a knot in the suture outside of the body, and bringing the knot into the desired position by means of said laparoscopic ligator.

column12: TOTALLY SUBMERGED PRESSURIZED PULP WASHER AND METHOD OF OPERATION THEREOF
column13: A pulp mat is formed on a surface of a permeable rotating drum disposed in a pressurized liquid filled washing apparatus. Pressurized washing liquid is delivered under the force of gravity or a hydrostatic head from a wash liquid reservoir. The wash liquid reservoir includes both wash liquid and gas supplied from a filtrate reservoir. The gas/liquid interface in the wash liquid reservoir is hydraulically disposed above the top of the washer vat to thereby provide a hydrostatic head between the wash liquid reservoir and the washer vat. The interface is monitored and used to control the speed of the rotating drum. In the event the gas/liquid interface rises above a predetermined optimum value for the current operating speed of the drum, the speed of the drum is increased in order to avoid mat collapse and optimize washing efficiency. In the event the gas/liquid interface drops below a predetermined optimum level, the speed of the drum is reduced to increase washing efficiency.
column15: CLARKE-POUNDER IAN JAMES HENRY

column12: Reactivation of deactivated hydrocarbon conversion catalyst by ultrasonic insonation
column13: Catalysts used in hydrocarbon conversion operations are subject to "permanent" deactivation after successive use and regeneration. column13: A hose monitoring system for an inflight refuelling system comprising a hose deployment system for deploying and retracting a hose 4 in and out of an aircraft, an observation system including sensing device(s) 51a, 51b, 51c observing the hose as it passes between the hose deployment system and aircraft exterior. Preferably, a plurality of sensing devices is radially distributed around the hose for visual assessment of the hose condition (e.g. hose wear, damage, deterioration) from different directions. column12: By-pass pressure control unit for IC engine fuel distribution circuit
column13: The control unit, for an ic. engine fuel distribution circuit, consists of a housing with a diaphragm valve (46) forming first and second chambers. The housing has a fuel inlet connecting the distribution pipe constantly to the second chamber, an outlet connected to the first chamber, and a valve seat between the chambers. The diaphragm is held against the seat by a spring (66). The diaphragm, the spring and the seat are designed and positioned so that when the pressure exerted by the fluid in the second chamber exceeds that applied to the diaphragm by the spring, the diaphragm moves away from the seat and links the second chamber with the by-pass fuel outlet via the first chamber.

column12: PROCESS FOR THE HYDROGENATION OF OLEFINS AND AROMATIC COMPOUNDS
column13: Olefins and aromatic compounds in mixed hydrocarbon streams boiling above about 200.degree.F are hydrogenated at a temperature ranging between about 400.degree.F-720.degree.F using a zeolitecontaining catalyst that has been treated with a hydrocarbon stream relatively high in organic nitrogen compounds to suppress the cracking activity of the catalyst. The catalyst comprises (1) an amorphous base component, (2) a crystalline aluminosilicate component preferably comprising 5-30 wt. % of the total catalyst and having a silica/alumina mole ratio of at least 2.5 and an alkali metal content of less than about 2.0 wt. % and (3) a transition metal hydrogenation component. The process is particularly useful in the manufacture of jet fuels and technical white oils and white oil bases with a minimum conversion of feed ( < 20%) to substantailly lower boiling products.

column13: 958,947. Protective arrangements; electric currents, converting &c. GENERAL ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. Aug. 24, 1962 [Aug. 24, 1961], No. 30562/61. Headings H2F and H2K. A power supply circuit including a semiconductor controlled inverter is provided with a thermal relay THB arranged to be energized when a switch 5 in series with the inverter is closed, a relay C to interrupt the operating circuit of the thermal relay (at C2) when A.C. is produced at the output side of the inverter, and means 15 to open the switch 5 when the thermal relay is operated if A.C. is not produced before the end of the timing period of the thermal relay. When the switch 5 is closed, a relay D closes contacts D1 to complete the circuit for a transistor oscillator, Fig. 3, controlling the inverter, a thermal relay THA closes contacts THAI to energize a relay E, and a relay A closes contacts A1. The relay E closes contacts E2 to complete the circuit for a contactor B and opens contacts E1 to deenergize the relays THA and A. The contactor B closes its contacts 9, 10 to complete the supply circuit to the inverter. As soon as the inverter supplies A.C., the relay C closes contacts C1 to maintain the contactor B energized and opens contacts C2 to open the circuits of the relays A, THA and THB. If relay C does not operate before relay A releases, contactor B opens. Subsequently, the thermal relay THA recloses its contacts THAI to re-energize the relay E so that the sequence of operation is repeated. If, after the contactor B has been closed three times, the relay C has not operated, the thermal relay THB closes its contacts THB1 to energize an electromagnet 15 to trip open the switch 5. A further thermal relay THC providing a longer time delay is controlled by the contacts 16 of a relay connected across the inverter output circuit. A rectifier 6 prevents operation should the circuit be connected with the wrong polarity. The inverter, Fig. 2, comprises two pairs of silicon controlled rectifiers 15A. . . 15D, the rectifiers of each pair being connected in series and* the pairs being connected between a negative input terminal 16 and the ends of a centre-tapped transformer primary winding 21. Each rectifier is shunted by a resistor 27 and a resistor 28 and a capacitor 29 in series so that transients in the D.C. supply are equally divided between the rectifiers of each pair. Rectifier elements 33, 34 improve the regulation characteristics of the inverter. The gating signals for the rectifiers 15A ... 15D are derived from a voltage regulator 5 and a transistor oscillator 4, Fig. 3, comprising transistors 46, 47 and a transformer 48 interconnected in the manner described in Specification 857,775, The transformer 48 has an additional primary winding 49 to which a synchronizing A.C. may be supplied by way of a transformer 50. Zener diodes 54, 55 limit the voltages of the secondary windings 51 . . . 53 before application to the rectifier gates. Specification 958,948 also is referred to.

[Also in Division G3] The electric inverter system described in Specification 958,947 includes a series output voltage regulator, the impedance of which increases if the output voltage falls to an abnormally low value, e.g. under short circuit conditions. The output voltage is automatically maintained constant under normal conditions by a series transductor 56 having a control winding 60 which is energized by an error signal derived from a circuit including transistors 73, 76. The output voltage is applied to the primary winding 66 of a transformer 65; a voltage proportional to this output voltage is derived from a secondary winding 68, is rectified and smoothed, and is applied over a potentiometer 72 to the base of transistor 73 which, together with a reference Zener diode 74 acts as a comparator to deliver an error signal which is applied by way of transistor 76 to the control winding 60, whereby the impedance of transductor 56 is varied in dependence upon output voltage variations. If, however, the output voltage falls to a very low value, positive feedback provided by a winding 59 causes the impedance of transductor 56 to increase, whereby a finite load impedance is presented to the inverter which is thus protected against an excessive load current. The feedback winding 59 is connected to a rectifier circuit 63 so that it is energized by a rectified portion of the output of the inverter system. A circuit utilizing silicon controlled rectifiers may replace the transductor' 56. Specification 857,775 also is referred to.

column12: Tetra-alkyl titanates as bonding agents for thermoplastic propellants
column13: A process is disclosed for improving the mechanical properties and procesility of thermoplastic composite propellants achieved by incorporation in the propellant of from about 0.1% to 1.0% of an organic titanate of the general formula Ti(OR).sub.4, where R represents a common alkyl group. The process comprises dissolving in an excess amount of a volatile organic solvent a thermoplastic elastomer which consists of hard segments having substantially crystalline properties and soft segments having substantially amorphous properties. The hard segments impart rigid properties to a solid propellant composition with which it is combined, and the soft segments imparting rubbery properties to a solid propellant composition with which it is combined. The Ti(OR).sub.4 functions as a medium between the surface of the ammonium perchlorate (AP) oxidizer and the thermoplastic elastomer to improve processability and to provide a bonding substrate to enhance the adhesive bond between the AP and the thermoplastic elastomer. After solvent removal, the propellant pellets are heat formed in a mold, the mold is cooled, and the molded product is released in the form of a solid propellant grain.

column13: On détermine la concentration d'une espèce ionique (par exemple K+) à l'aide d'une électrode sensible aux ions comportant une membrane appropriée (par exemple de la valinomycine dans du PVC plastifié). Afin de compléter la demi cellule on utilise, à la place d'une électrode de référence classique, une électrode ayant une membrane identique mais ne comportant pas le constituant produisant la réponse de sélection d'ions (par exemple du PVC plastifié). On peut alors fabriquer les électrodes de travail et de référence de manière sensiblement identique afin d'annuler les éléments interférentiels. On évite ainsi les difficultés associées aux doubles jonctions.

column13: A dual crankshaft internal combustion engine is symmetrically constructed to form a perfectly balanced engine assembly. A first crankshaft, having a first end, a second end, and being formed of a shape and with a torsional flexibility, is housed within a cylinder block and connected to a first series of cooperating pistons and cylinders. A second crankshaft, having a first end and a second end, is formed of substantially the same shape as the first crankshaft and has substantially the same torsional flexibility as the first crankshaft. The second crankshaft is also housed within the cylinder block and connected to a second series of cooperating pistons and cylinders, while being positioned parallel to the first crankshaft, with the first end of the first crankshaft being positioned adjacent to the second end of the second crankshaft.

column12: Process for the hydrogenation of olefins and aromatic compounds
column13: Olefins and aromatic compounds in mixed hydrocarbon streams boiling above about 200.degree. F. are hydrogenated at a temperature ranging between about 400.degree. F.-720.degree. F. using a zeolite-containing catalyst that has been treated with a hydrocarbon stream relatively high in organic nitrogen compounds to suppress the cracking activity of the catalyst. The catalyst comprises (1) an amorphous base component, (2) a crystalline aluminosilicate component preferably comprising 5-30 wt. % of the total catalyst and having a silica/alumina mole ratio of at least 2.5 and an alkali metal content of less than about 2.0 wt. %, and (3) a transition metal hydrogenation component. The process is particularly useful in the manufacture of jet fuels and technical white oils and white oil bases with a minimum conversion of feed (<20%) to substantially lower boiling products.

Roundabouts.-Roundabouts are constructed so that the cars receive a similar motion to cars moving on a circular switchback track, but the cars are suspended by means of wires from a rotating frame, and the vertical motion of the cars is obtained by drawing the suspending-wires n and out by means of an eccentric. Each car K is suspended from a jib J, supported by spars B, G, by means of two wire ropes H, one at each end of the car, each rope H being provided with a ring L, from which are suspended two ropes attached respectively to the front end of one car and the rear of the adjacent car. The spars B are attached to a plate S which moves round with the sbaft A. The shaft A is driven by means of a band U formed in two halves capable of being adjusted by means of bolts and springs so as to engage a friction drum T, fixed to the plate S. The band V is connected to the main driving-wheel W, loosely mounted on the shaft A and driven by suitable power. The rotation of the shaft A drives an eccentric E, loosely mounted on the shaft, through the operation of bevelwheels D, 0, M, the last being loosely mounted on an arm N fixed to the shaft A. This gearing causes the eccentric E to revolve in the opposite direction to the shaft A. The gearing may be arranged so that the eccentric revolves at a different rate from the shaft A. The eccentric E is surrounded by a ring or strap R running on rollers, and the ropes H, which are suitably guided by pulleys &c., are attached to the strap R, so that, for each revolution of the eccentric E, the cars K rise and fall through a certain distance. The cars K are guided in their vertical motions by rods Q attached to the beams C, which are connected to the cars by means of pins Z, about which the cars oscillate. The rods Q move through guides V on the spars G, and serve to prevent the cars from moving outwards by centrifugal force.

column13: Ethylenically unsaturated hydrocarbons are polymerised in the presence of a liquid medium and a catalyst comprising an aluminium halide and an inorganic mercury derivative preferably a compound capable of forming some sort of loose complex with the halide. The term "inorganic mercury derivative" includes a salt of mercury with an organic acid but does not include a carbon-metal bond. Derivatives of mercury mentioned are mercuric chloride, bromide, iodide, nitrate, sulphide, cyanide, chromate, and oxide, potassium mercuri-iodide, and mercuric acetate. The halide may be aluminium chloride or bromide. The hydrocarbon may be ethylene, propylene, butylene, pentene, butadiene 1 : 3, styrene, or alpha-methylstyrene, and mixtures. The catalyst can if desired be supported on an inert carrier, e.g. charcoal or silica gel. The liquid medium may be trichloroethylene, tetrachloroethylene, carbon tetrachloride, chloroform, ethylene dibromide, cyclohexane, n-decane, n-hexane, n-heptane, n-dodecane, stannic tetrachloride, and silicon tetrachloride.ALSO:A catalyst for polymerizing ethylenically unsaturated hydrocarbons in the presence of a liquid medium comprises an aluminium halide and an inorganic mercury derivative e.g. a compound capable of forming some sort of loose complex with the halide. The term "inorganic mercury derivative" includes a salt of mercury with an organic acid. The catalyst may be supported on an inert carrier e.g. charcoal or silica gel. The two components may be deposited on the carrier by impregnating the carrier with a solution of the components and drying the carrier, or by impregnating the carrier with the mercury derivative and adding a solution of the aluminium halide to the impregnated carrier. Derivatives of mercury mentioned are mercuric chloride, bromide, iodide, nitrate, sulphide, cyanide, chromate, and oxide, potassium mercuri-iodide, and mercuric acetate. The halide may be aluminium bromide or chloride. The liquid medium may be organic or inorganic e.g. trichloroethylene, tetrachloroethylene, carbon tetrachloride, chloroform, ethylene dibromide, cyclohexane, n-decane, n-hexane, n-heptane, n-dodecane, stannic tetrachloride, or silicon tetrachloride.

column12: Improvements relating to electrical spark gap discharge apparatus
column13: 781,378. Spark gaps. METROPOLITANVICKERS ELECTRICAL CO., Ltd. July 6, 1955 [July 16, 1954], No. 20823/54. Class 39(1). The centre electrode of a double spark gap is formed in two parts B1 and B2 connected together through a condenser C1 and resistor R3 and each part has an associated triggering electrode P 1 or P 2 . The parts B 1 and B 2 are connected to the mid-point of a potential divider R 1 R 2 which is connected between the outer electrodes A and C. A positive pulse generated at the mid-point of the potential divider by a pulse transformer T is applied between the coupling condenser C1 and the electrode P 2 causing breakdown of P 2 B 2 and then, as condenser C 1 charges up, P 1 B 1 . If C is positive with respect to A gap AB 1 breaks down followed by gap CB 2 . If C is negative with respect to A gap CB2 breaks down followed by gap AB 1 . The arrangement may be connected as a triggering device in the first stage of an impulse generator and ensures that when the generator polarity is reversed there is always an outer electrode which is negative with respect to the centre electrode and facing a triggering- electrode which is positive with respect to its associated electrode, which are the optimum conditions when triggering a spark gap. The spark-gap is designed to operate in still air at atmospheric pressure but may be enclosed in an envelope filled with gas at a pressure greater than atmospheric. Spark quenching means such as an air blast may also be provided. The centre electrode, Fig. 2, comprises two hemispheres 1, 2 for example of copper fitted with molybdenum inserts 3, 4 having central holes 5, 6 through which project molybdenum triggering rods 7, 8 held in brass bushings 9, 10 attached by screws, which are preferably staggered to prevent electrical breakdown, to an insulating disc 11 for example of ebonite to which the hemispheres 1, 2 are also attached. The triggering rods 7, 8 are surrounded by glass tubes 12, 13 which are ground at one end and fastened at the other end by wax to the brass bushings 9, 10. A resistor 14 and condenser 15 are connected inside the electrode so that only the two connections to the pulse transformer are brought out via channels in the disc 11. Specification 578,510 [Group XL] is referred to.

column13: High power gas laser using an arrangement forming a lasing cavity with an optical axis and an inlet and outlet for a gaseous lasing medium, plus an anode and a cathode. A linear array of anode segments is pref. employed and devices used to cool both the anode and the cathode. column13: 122,476. Crawley, C. H., Starkey, M. E., and Clarke, W. E. Jan. 24, 1918. Ploughs.-Tractor ploughs, in which the side wheels are mounted on crank-axles on parallel crank-shafts, are adapted to be raised and lowered by means of a member mounted loosely on one of the crank-shafts and geared to and rotating with the corresponding side wheel, means being provided for locking the rotating member to the crankshaft when required, for connecting the two crankshafts together so that the angular movement of the one is communicated in reduced degree to the other, and for simultaneously tilting the standard of the rear wheel. The crank-shafts A<2>, B<2> are furnished with arms D, D' connected by a link D<2>, the effective length of the arm D being variable. The axle A<1> of the land-wheel A is carried by a disk C on the shaft A<2>. A brake-drum F is mounted loosely on the shaft A<2> and is connected to the wheel A by chain gearing. The plough is raised by locking the drum F to the disk C by means of a brake-band H actuated by means of a lever J<2> and cord J<3> and provided with a stud H' to enter a recess in the drum F. The brake is released, when the plough is raised, by the lever J<2> coming into contact with a guide-pulley E<3>, A clutch may be substituted for the brake-drum F and band H, and the wheel may have grips on its periphery to prevent skidding. A duplicate locking arrangement may be provided to allow of the plough being lowered by reversing the tractor; or a pivoted and spring-controlled tipping-lever K, K<1> may be provided to throw the cranks back over their vertical centres, so as to allow the plough to fall under its own weight. The lever K, K' is actuated by means of a cord K<3> and engages a roller L on the arm D<1>. The depth of furrow is varied by adjusting a stop-piece D<4>, which engages with a frame-stay E' when the plough is lowered. The socket N for the standard M<2> of the rear wheel M is pivoted on a horizontal pivot N', and is tilted by a lever 0 connected to the arm D by a link P. A stop N<3> limits the move. ment when the plough is run back. The wheel M is of the self-steering type It is always returned to its normal track position by a spring-actuated plunger R engaging a flat face on a collar R' on the standard M<2>.

column12: Heat exchanger and double distillation column
column13: A heat exchanger is provided which is suitable for use as a condenser/reboiler in a double distillation column. The heat exchanger has alternating first and second passages and a reservoir located above the first and second passages for receiving a first fluid and for containing a froth. A series of orifices can be provided by a distributor tray to provide flow communication between the reservoir and the first passages to allow at least a liquid phase of the froth to weep into the first passages and to be partly vaporized through indirect heat exchange with a second fluid flowing through the second passages. The partial vaporization produces a vapor phase of the froth which can at least in part escape from the orifices and interact with the first fluid to thereby form the froth. A remaining part of the liquid phase, not vaporized through the indirect heat exchange, is discharged from the bottom of the first passages into a sump. The weeping inlet of the liquid phase into the first passages allows for the automatic replenishment of the first passages due to flow mal-distribution.
column15: SATCHELL JR DONALD PRENTICE;;NATARAJAN VENKAT;;CLARKE RICHARD HENRY

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.

column13: An air-to-air coupling 13 (e.g. for receiving a probe in probe-and-drogue refuelling) comprises retaining members 19, 27 for interacting with a further member (e.g. a refuelling probe) to hold the further member in place. An active drive system 39, 21 may drive the holding members and may thereby also actively drive the further member into place. Alternatively the active drive 39, 21 may drive another member such as a locking member 31 to hold the retaining members 19, 27 in position once the further member is in place. The active drive releases the retaining members 19, 27 or moves them out of position to allow the further member to be removed. This allows the further member to be inserted and removed with a lower force than is used to hold it in place. The coupling may also be used for in-air recovery of an unmanned aircraft.

column13: A cryogenic engine system and method for delivering cryogen to a cryogenic engine, the system includes a tank 10 for storing liquid cryogen, a cryogenic engine 16, a pump 12 configured to pressurise cryogen from the tank, a first conduit 14 for transporting cryogen between the pump and the cryogenic engine, a second conduit 26 for transporting cryogen from the pump back to the tank, and a first valve 30 disposed in the second conduit for controlling the flow of cryogen from the pump back to the tank. A pre-mixing system for a cryogenic engine and a method for mixing cryogen with a heat exchange fluid (HEF) are also provided, the mixing system may include a chamber 18, 20 with a plurality of first inlets and second inlets arranged so that the cryogen and heat exchange fluid flow in opposite directions. In one arrangement a plurality of mixing chambers connected in parallel 18, 20 are used.

column12: Process monitoring and control using self-validating sensors
column13: Self-validating (SEVA) sensors implemented in a control process provide various metrics regarding sensed variables to a central control unit. Specifically, SEVA sensors provide measurements of the variables and validity information about the measurements, which may include fault information about the sensors themselves. A control unit utilizes the various SEVA metrics even when large numbers of SEVA sensors are used, a situation that is otherwise problematic due to difficulties in assimilating data from multiple SEVA sensors. Accordingly, the control unit distinguishes sensor faults from actual process changes, and responds as needed, even when large numbers of SEVA sensors are implemented together. Specifically, the monitoring and control unit assimilates signals from multiple SEVA sensors using a multi-variate statistical analysis, and compares results of this analysis with a model characterizing behavior of the process (where the model may take into account actuator position information) and/or historical statistical data.

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.

column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a digital mass flowmeter capable of applying correct and sophisticated control algorithms which has larger reactivity, higher precision, and larger adaptability than conventional analog fashions.

SOLUTION: The digital flowmeter 100 includes a vibro-conduit, a driving circuit 115 connected to the conduit to have an operationality forcing motion to the conduit, and a sensor 110 connected to the conduit to have operationality detecting motion of the conduit. A digital controller 105 is connected between the driving circuit and the sensor. The digital controller 105 includes a circuit, which receives sensor signals from the sensor to produce a driving signal from the sensor signal using a digital signal processing and outputs a driving signal to the driving circuit to produce a measured value of the property of a material flowing through the conduit from a signal of the sensor.

COPYRIGHT: (C)2007,JPO&INPIT
column15: HENRY P MANUS;;CLARKE W DAVID;;VIGNOS H JAMES

column13: A controller for a flowmeter includes an input module operable to receive a sensor signal from a sensor connected to a vibratable flowtube. The sensor signal is related to a fluid flow through the flowtube. The controller also includes a signal processing system operable to receive the sensor signal, determine sensor signal characteristics, and output drive signal characteristics for a drive signal applied to the flowtube. An output module is operable to output the drive signal to the flowtube and a control system is operable to modify the drive signal and thereby maintain oscillation of the flowtube during a transition of the flowtube from a substantially empty state to a substantially full state.
column15: HENRY MANUS P;;CLARKE DAVID W;;VIGNOS JAMES H

column13: A process monitoring unit (14) and sensors (SEVA 1-36) having self-inspection capability, are provided in the higher and lower levels of the monitoring system. The monitoring unit monitors output signals of the sensors and identifies every significant change of the process conditions, and determines whether the change occurs as a result of the change in characteristics of a certain sensor or due to actual change in process conditions. An Independent claim is also included for process monitoring unit.

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.
column15: HENRY MANUS P;;CLARKE DAVID W;;VIGNOS JAMES H

column13: A flowmeter includes a vibratable conduit, a driver connected to the conduit and operable to impart motion to the conduit, and a sensor connected to the conduit and operable to sense the motion of the conduit. A control and measurement system is connected to the driver and the sensor. The control and measurement system includes circuitry to receive a sensor signal from the sensor, generate a drive signal based on the sensor signal, supply the drive signal to the driver, and generate a measurement of a property of material flowing through the conduit based on the sensor signal.
column15: HENRY MANUS P;;CLARKE DAVID W;;VIGNOS JAMES H

column13: A controller for a flowmeter includes an input module operable to receive a sensor signal from a sensor connected to a vibratable flowtube. The sensor signal is related to a fluid flow through the flowtube. The controller also includes a signal processing system operable to receive the sensor signal, determine sensor signal characteristics, and output drive signal characteristics for a drive signal applied to the flowtube. An output module is operable to output the drive signal to the flowtube and a control system is operable to modify the drive signal and thereby maintain oscillation of the flowtube during a transition of the flowtube from a substantially empty state to a substantially full state.

column13: Lipid vesicle particles capable of being targeted to a cell type of interest, said particle incorporating a peptide which is responsive to a predetermined metabolic signal from the targeted cell so as to modulate the permeability of the particle, said particle further incorporating a species to be targeted to the cell which is activated on said modulation of permeability. The particles may be used in methods for detecting cells, methods of treating cells and also therapeutically.

column12: COMPOSICION FARMACEUTICA DE FORMOTEROL Y PROPIONATO DE FLUTICASONA
column13: SE REFIERE A UNA COMPOSICION FARMACEUTICA QUE COMPRENDE: a)DE 3µg A 36µg DE FUMARATO DE FORMOTEROL DIHIDRATO N-[2-HIDROXI-5-(1-HIDROXI-2-((2-(4-METOXIFENIL)-1-METILETIL)AMINO)-ETIL)FENIL]-FORMAMIDA (BRONCODILATADOR); b)DE 25µg A 500µg DE PROPIONATO DE FLUTICASONA 6-ALFA,9-ALFA-DIFLUORO-11-BETA-HIDROXI-16-ALFA-METIL-3-OXO-17-ALFA-PROPIONILOXIANDROSTA-1,4-DIEN-17-BETA CARBOTIOATO DE S FLUOROMETILO (CORTICOSTEROIDE ANTIINFLAMATORIO); c)DE 25mg A 50mg DE UN VEHICULO. LA COMPOSICION SE CARACTERIZA POR PRESENTARSE EN FORMA DE AEROSOL, INHALABLE, ATOMIZABLE, QUE COMPRENDE UNA MEZCLA SOLUCION O DISPERSION EN UN PROPELENTE EN UN MEDIO ACUOSO, ORGANICO O ACUOSO/ORGANICO; CUANDO LA COMPOSICION SE PRESENTA EN FORMA DE POLVO CON UN DIAMETRO DE PARTICULAS DE 10µ, JUNTO CON UN VEHICULO COMO SACARIDO Y LACTOSA; SIENDO LA PROPORCION EN PESO DEL FORMOTEROL A FLUTICASONA 3:1 A 1:3000. LA COMPOSICION PUEDE SER UTIL PARA EL TRATAMIENTO DE ENFERMEDAD INFLAMATORIA U OBSTRUCTIVA DE LAS VIAS AEREAS

column12: LUBRICATING GREASE FOR ROCK DRILL BITS AND BITS SO LUBRICATED
column13:
@ A lubricating grease suitable for use in rock drill bits comprises:
 (1) a major proportion of a mineral or synthetic hydrocarbon base oil, (2) from 3 to 15% wt by weight of the grease of a lithium complex soap as the sole thickener, and (3) from 5 to 20% wt by weight of the grease of molybdenum disulphide particles as extreme pressure additive. Such a grease has the required lubrificating qualities and the required flow properties for use in rock drill bits having a grease reservoir (e.g. a pressure equalisation chamber) and channels connecting the reservoir to the bearing surfaces.

column13: An air-to-air coupling 13 for a probe-and-drogue system is mounted on a first aircraft, the coupling has a number of retainers 19 moving between a holding position (fig.7), in which they interact with a suitably shaped part 9 on a second aircraft, and a release position (fig.4). The coupling has a drive system 21,23 which responds to latching/release signals to urge the retaining members towards/away from, and/or hold them in/move them from, the holding position. Preferably, the drive system has a controller which responds to sensors detecting the presence of the shaped part. The retainers may rotate and interact with the shaped part at an intermediate position (fig.6), before reaching the holding position. The retainers are biased towards the holding position, with the driving system arranged to adjust its opposition to the bias. A cable, or refuelling hose, connected to a drogue may be connected to the coupling. A fuel line with a valve may also be provided, the valve biased into a closed position to close the fuel line and opened by the retainers when driven into the holding position, before pressurised fuel is supplied.

column13: An air-to-air coupling 13 (e.g. for receiving a probe in probe-and-drogue refuelling) comprises retaining members 19, 27 for interacting with a further member (e.g. a refuelling probe) to hold the further member in place. An active drive system 39, 21 may drive the holding members and may thereby also actively drive the further member into place. Alternatively the active drive 39, 21 may drive another member such as a locking member 31 to hold the retaining members 19, 27 in position once the further member is in place. The active drive releases the retaining members 19, 27 or moves them out of position to allow the further member to be removed. This allows the further member to be inserted and removed with a lower force than is used to hold it in place. The coupling may also be used for in-air recovery of an unmanned aircraft.

column13: A digital flowmeter includes a vibratable conduit, a driver connected to the conduit and operable to impart motion to the conduit, and a sensor connected to the conduit and operable to sense the motion of the conduit. A control and measurement system is connected to the driver and the sensor. The control and measurement system includes circuitry to receive a sensor signal from the sensor, generate a drive signal based on the sensor signal using digital signal processing, supply the drive signal to the driver, and generate a measurement of a property of a two-phase material flowing through the conduit based on the signal from the sensor.
column15: HENRY MANUS P;;CLARKE DAVID W;;VIGNOS JAMES H

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.

column13: A controller for a flowmeter includes an input module operable to receive a sensor signal from a sensor connected to a vibratable flowtube. The controller also includes a signal processing system operable to receive the sensor signal, determine sensor signal characteristics, and output drive signal characteristics for a drive signal applied to the flowtube. An output module is operable to output the drive signal to the flowtube and a control system is operable to modify the drive signal and thereby maintain oscillation of the flowtube during a transition of the flowtube from a substantially empty state to a substantially full state.

column13: Lipid vesicle particles capable of being targeted to a cell type of interest, said particle incorporating a peptide which is responsive to a predetermined metabolic signal from the targeted cell so as to modulate the permeability of the particle, said particle further incorporating a species to be targeted to the cell which is activated on said modulation of permeability. The particles may be used in methods for detecting cells, methods of treating cells and also therapeutically.

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.

column12: Combination of formoterol and mometasone furoate for treating asthma
column13: In the present invention, there is disclosed a medicament containing, separately or together, (A) formoterol or a pharmaceutically acceptable salt thereof or a solvate of formoterol or a solvate of the salt and (B) mometasone furoate, for simultaneous, sequential or separate administration in the treatment of an inflammatory or obstructive airways diseases.

column12: Lubricating grease for rock drill bits and bits so lubricated.
column13:
@ A lubricating grease suitable for use in rock drill bits comprises:
 (1) a major proportion of a mineral or synthetic hydrocarbon base oil, (2) from 3 to 15% wt by weight of the grease of a lithium complex soap as the sole thickener, and (3) from 5 to 20% wt by weight of the grease of molybdenum disulphide particles as extreme pressure additive. Such a grease has the required lubrificating qualities and the required flow properties for use in rock drill bits having a grease reservoir (e.g. a pressure equalisation chamber) and channels connecting the reservoir to the bearing surfaces.

column12: INTEGRATED POWER AND COOLING ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL SYSTEM
column13: An environmental control system has an air cycle machine that includes a compressor (38), a cooling turbine (34), a motor/generator (36), and a power turbine (40) all mounted on a single shaft (32). The power turbine receives bleed air from the aircraft's engine (12) and has a variable geometry inlet nozzle (42) that adjusts the air flow rate therethrough without significant throttling. Downstream of the nozzle the power turbine extracts the expansion energy from the bleed air while cooling it. This is used to drive the other components of the air cycle machine, and in particular the motor/generator which generates electricity.
column15: CLAEYS HENRY M;;CLARKE KATHRINE J;;MATULICH DAN S

column13: 125,806. Crawley, C. H., Starkey, M. E., and Clarke, W. E. June 4, 1918. Ploughs. - In a combined skim and disk coulter, the two coulters are carried by a member which is pivoted on a vertical support between them and is free to swing about it through a limited angle, so that the combined coulter mav adjust itself to the line of work. The pivoted member comprises a forked arm C carrying the disk coulter A. It is mounted loosely on an adjustable cranked standard D and is held in place by a collar G fitting in a recessed boss C<1> and secured by a set-screw G<1>. Angular movement is limited by the engagement of the boss C' with an extension G<2> of the collar G, or by other means. The skim coulter H is carried by a bracket J adjustably attached to an extension of the boss C<1>.

column13: A pneumatic tyre for a vehicle comprising a carcass ply (4) extending between two bead regions and passing through a tread region (1) which extends between two tread contact edges, a tread region (1) reinforcing breaker (2) radially outwards of the carcass (4) in the tread region (1) and a ground contacting tread surface (10) curved in the axial direction characterised in that the curvature of the outer tread surface (10) when the tyre is mounted on a wheel rim (11) and normally inflated has a continuously decreasing radius from a point P which is at a distance SP in the axial direction from the tyre circumferential centreline (C) equal to 20% of the distance from the tread centre to the adjacent tread contact edge.
column15: WILLIAMS ARTHUR ROGER;;CLARKE DAVID HENRY;;NOCK NIGEL GERARD

column13: A digital flowmeter includes a vibratable conduit, a driver connected to the conduit and operable to impart motion to the conduit, and a sensor connected to the conduit and operable to sense the motion of the conduit. A control and measurement system is connected to the driver and the sensor. The control and measurement system includes circuitry to receive a sensor signal from the sensor, generate a drive signal based on the sensor signal using digital signal processing, supply the drive signal to the driver, and generate a measurement of a property of a two-phase material flowing through the conduit based on the signal from the sensor.

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.

column13: A control and measurement system for a coriolis flowmeter having a flowtube, a driver adapted to vibrate the flowtube, and a pair of sensors adapted to generate signals indicative of movement of the flowtube when it is being vibrated by the driver, wherein the sensors are positioned relative to one another so the signals from the sensors are indicative of a mass flow rate of fluid through the flowtube. A digital drive signal generator is adapted to generate a variable digital drive signal for controlling operation of the driver. The digital drive signal generator can be adapted to cause the driver to resist motion of the flowtube during a first time period and amplify motion of the flowtube during a second time period. The digital drive signal generator can also be adapted to initiate motion of the flowtube by sending one or more square wave signals to the driver.

column12: Heat exchanger and double distillation column
column13: A heat exchanger is provided which is suitable for use as a condenser/reboiler in a double distillation column. The heat exchanger has alternating first and second passages and a reservoir located above the first and second passages for receiving a first fluid and for containing a froth. A series of orifices can be provided by a distributor tray to provide flow communication between the reservoir and the first passages to allow at least a liquid phase of the froth to weep into the first passages and to be partly vaporised through indirect heat exchange with a second fluid flowing through the second passages. The partial vaporisation produces a vapour phase of the froth which can at least in part escape from the orifices and interact with the first fluid to thereby form the froth. A remaining part of the liquid phase, not vaporised through the indirect heat exchange, is discharged from the bottom of the first passages into a sump. The weeping inlet of the liquid phase into the first passages allows for the automatic replenishment of the first passages due to flow mal-distribution.

column13: Un acoplamiento aire-aire 13 (por ejemplo, para recibir una sonda en reabastecimiento de combustible de sonda y embudo) comprende miembros de retención 19, 27 para interactuar con otro miembro (por ejemplo, una sonda de reabastecimiento) para mantener el miembro adicional en su lugar. Un sistema de accionamiento activo 39, 21 puede accionar los elementos de sujeción y, por lo tanto, también puede accionar activamente el otro elemento en su lugar. Alternativamente, el accionamiento activo 39, 21 puede impulsar otro elemento, como un elemento de bloqueo 31, para mantener los elementos de retención 19, 27 en posición una vez que el otro elemento esté en su lugar. El accionamiento activo libera los miembros de retención 19, 27 o los mueve fuera de su posición para permitir que se retire el miembro adicional. Esto permite insertar y retirar el miembro adicional con una fuerza menor que la utilizada para mantenerlo en su lugar. El acoplamiento también se puede utilizar para la recuperación en el aire de una aeronave no tripulada. (Traducción automática con Google Translate, sin valor legal)

column13: A heat exchanger for use within a sump to condense an vapor and to vaporize the liquid. In such manner, part of the liquid is vaporized within the down flow stage and the remainder is vaporized within the thermosiphon stage or stages.

column12: Process monitoring and control using self-validating sensors
column13: A multi-level (hierarchical) process monitoring system comprises a process monitoring unit (14), at a higher level of the system, and a plurality of sensors (SEVA 1, SEVA 2 ... SEVA 36) at a lower level of the system, at least one of the sensors having SEVA capability (self-validating capability), the sensors being adapted to provide respective measurement values of respective process variables to said monitoring unit, said monitoring unit being so arranged as to monitor the outputs of the sensors and to identify any significant apparent change in the process conditions as detected from an overview of said sensor outputs, and on detection of an apparent significant change, to request additional status information from at least one of the SEVA sensor/s to determine whether the apparent change is in reality due to a change in the characteristics of a particular SEVA sensor rather than an actual significant change in the process conditions.

column12: Heat exchanger and double distillation column
column13: A heat exchanger is provided which is suitable for use as a condenser/reboiler in a double distillation column. The heat exchanger has alternating first and second passages and a reservoir located above the first and second passages for receiving a first fluid and for containing a froth. A series of orifices can be provided by a distributor tray to provide flow communication between the reservoir and the first passages to allow at least a liquid phase of the froth to weep into the first passages and to be partly vaporised through indirect heat exchange with a second fluid flowing through the second passages. The partial vaporisation produces a vapour phase of the froth which can at least in part escape from the orifices and interact with the first fluid to thereby form the froth. A remaining part of the liquid phase, not vaporised through the indirect heat exchange, is discharged from the bottom of the first passages into a sump. The weeping inlet of the liquid phase into the first passages allows for the automatic replenishment of the first passages due to flow mal-distribution.
